06416nam a22010815i 9780813553887DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20132013nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2012005040  a97808135538877 a10.36019/97808135538872doi  a(DE-B1597)529400  a(OCoLC)1163878601  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN1992.8.A34bW38 2012 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a791.4508996073  aAP 393832rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7473:1024400aWatching While Black :bCentering the Television of Black Audiences /ced. by Beretta E. Smith-Shomade. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b33 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTelevision scholarship has substantially ignored programming aimed at Black audiences despite a few sweeping histories and critiques. In this volume, the first of its kind, contributors examine the televisual diversity, complexity, and cultural imperatives manifest in programming directed at a Black and marginalized audience. Watching While Black considers its subject from an entirely new angle in an attempt to understand the lives, motivations, distinctions, kindred lines, and individuality of various Black groups and suggest what television might be like if such diversity permeated beyond specialized enclaves. It looks at the macro structures of ownership, producing, casting, and advertising that all inform production, and then delves into television programming crafted to appeal to black audiences—historic and contemporary, domestic and worldwide. Chapters rethink such historically significant programs as Roots and Black Journal, such seemingly innocuous programs as Fat Albert and bro’Town, and such contemporary and culturally complicated programs as Noah’s Arc, Treme, and The Boondocks. The book makes a case for the centrality of these programs while always recognizing the racial dynamics that continue to shape Black representation on the small screen. Painting a decidedly introspective portrait across forty years of Black television, Watching While Black sheds much-needed light on under-examined demographics, broadens common audience considerations, and gives deference to the the preferences of audiences and producers of Black-targeted programming.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAfrican American television viewers. 0aAfrican Americans on television. 0aTelevision broadcastingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAcham, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAcham, Christine.1 aBurton, Nsenga K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurton, Nsenga.1 aCavalcante, Andre M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavalcante, Andre.1 aColeman, Robin Means.1 aColeman, Robin R. Means, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunningham, Mark D.1 aCunningham, Mark D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Jennifer.1 aGates, Racquel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGates, Racquel.1 aGillam, Reighan Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillam, Reighan.1 aHavens, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHavens, Timothy.1 aHeitner, Devorah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeitner, Devorah.1 aLeDuff, Kim M.1 aLeduff, Kim M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 